    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. To explain the physics of the pitot tube, let's dive into the technical details.\n\nThe pitot tube measures airspeed by using the principle of dynamic pressure, which is the pressure exerted by a fluid (in this case, air) due to its velocity. The pitot tube is typically connected to a static port, which measures the static pressure of the air, and a pitot static system, which measures the dynamic pressure of the air.\n\nThe pressure differential between the two ports is proportional to the airspeed. When the air flows over the pitot tube, it creates a pressure differential between the pitot port and the static port. This pressure differential is then measured by the pressure sensor, which converts it into an electrical signal that represents the airspeed.\n\nThe key is that the pressure differential is directly proportional to the airspeed. As the airspeed increases, the pressure differential also increases, and vice versa. This allows the pressure sensor to accurately measure the airspeed of the aircraft.\n\nNow, if the pitot tube becomes blocked, the pressure differential is disrupted, and the pressure sensor can't accurately measure the airspeed. This can lead to inaccurate readings, which can be",
